<h1 id="skupper-security">Skupper security</h1>
<div id="preamble">
<div class="sectionbody">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Skupper securely connects your services with TLS authentication and encryption.
See how Skupper enables you to deploy your application securely across Kubernetes clusters.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="sect1">
<h2 id="skupper-security-challenges">Security challenges in the cloud</h2>
<div class="sectionbody">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Moving an application to the cloud raises security risks.
Either your services must be exposed to the public internet, or you must adopt complex layer 3 network controls like VPNs, firewall rules, and access policies.</p>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Increasing the challenge, layer 3 network controls do not extend easily to multiple clusters.
These network controls must be duplicated for each cluster.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="sect1">
<h2 id="service-network-isolation">Built-in network isolation</h2>
<div class="sectionbody">
<div class="paragraph">
<p>Skupper provides default, built-in security that scales across clusters and clouds.
In a Skupper network, the connections between Skupper routers are secured with mutual TLS using a private, dedicated certificate authority (CA).
Each router is uniquely identified by its own certificate.</p>
</div>
<div class="imageblock">
<div class="content">
<img src="../images/clusters-tls.svg" alt="clusters tls">
</div>
</div>
<div class="paragraph">
<p>This means that the Skupper network is isolated from external access, preventing security risks such as lateral attacks, malware infestations, and data exfiltration.</p>
</div>
